    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:edc5440c-c70f-4893-aebc-91a8998954f9",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 5-year-old boy who appears tired, flushed, and clingy during the visit, sitting on his caregiver’s lap and swallowing carefully because of throat pain. He has had two days of fever, decreased appetite, and complaints that his throat \"hurts a lot,\" especially when drinking or eating solid foods. His voice is slightly muffled but he is breathing comfortably without stridor or drooling. On examination he has erythematous, enlarged tonsils with patchy white exudate and tender anterior cervical lymph nodes. He has mild nasal congestion but no significant cough.\n\nAt home, {patientName} is an active kindergarten-aged child who normally enjoys running outdoors, building with blocks, picture books, and pretend play with toy cars and animals. He lives with both parents and an older sister, and the family describes him as social, energetic, and usually a good eater. Over the last 48 hours he has been less playful, preferring to rest on the couch and asking for cool drinks and ice pops because warm foods worsen his throat pain.\n\nHe attends kindergarten five days a week, where several children have recently had upper respiratory infections. His parents report regular sleep habits, age-appropriate development, and up-to-date routine childhood immunizations. There is no exposure to tobacco smoke in the home. The family has a small circle of local relatives and friends who help with childcare, and his grandmother looked after him the day before presentation when his fever first increased.\n\nHis diet is generally balanced for his age, though like many children he can be selective with vegetables. He drinks milk and water regularly and has no known chronic feeding issues. The household is stable, and his parents are attentive to hydration, fever control, and follow-up care. Today they are mainly worried about his fever, refusal to eat, and whether he may need treatment for a throat infection."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:d770d06e-8a19-40a9-b8f1-3ab5775e8df0",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no known chronic medical conditions and has been meeting developmental milestones appropriately. He was born at term without major perinatal complications and has not had prior significant hospitalizations. His caregivers report occasional self-limited viral upper respiratory infections since starting daycare and kindergarten, but no history of recurrent streptococcal infections, peritonsillar abscess, asthma, congenital heart disease, or immunodeficiency.\n\nHis past medical history is notable only for mild seasonal allergic rhinitis during spring months, managed conservatively. He has never undergone surgery. He is fully immunized for age according to the routine childhood schedule. There is no history of medication overuse, and no recent antibiotic exposure in the last several months.\n\nLifestyle factors are typical for a healthy 5-year-old. {patientName} attends kindergarten, plays actively most days, and lives in a smoke-free home. Recent sick contacts at school are likely. Over the current illness, his parents have been giving fluids and age-appropriate acetaminophen for fever with partial relief. Urine output is slightly decreased but still present, suggesting mild reduced intake rather than severe dehydration."
          }
        ]
      }
